<HEADLINE>
<P>
RECORD RACK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHRIS WILLMAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MISSION U.K. -- -- * 1/2 
</P>
<P>
"Carved in Sand" 
</P>
<P>
Mercury/Polygram 
</P>
<P>
The passion, the passion. The horror, the horror. Listening to Mission U.K. 
frontman Wayne Hussey sing his dedicated innards out on song after song here, 
as if raging with every last gulp of air against the dying of some light or 
another, you may find yourself wondering,"Didn't Englishmen used to be 
reserved?" Moreover, you may wish they still were after suffering Hussey's 
unbridled intensity through 10 unforgiving, aggravated tracks. 
</P>
<P>
In the opening "Amelia," the most unsubtle look possible at father/daughter 
incest, the anger Hussey expresses is, of course, justified, if way over the 
top for musical purposes. This subject has obviously distressed him so that he 
stays in the same mood for the rest of the album, regardless of lyric. Whether 
it's realistic, socially relevant rock ("Grapes of Wrath," for the workin' man) 
or the plethora of moody love songs embracing tacky mythological imagery 
("Mistress of Avalon cast a spell" and so on), Hussey just sounds royally 
ticked off, with few breaks from the relentless gush of indignancy and ardor. 
CHRIS WILLMAN 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Recording Review 
</P>
