<HEADLINE>
<P>
POP EYE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By PATRICK GOLDSTEIN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
IDOL WORSHIP: Billy Idol is still in the hospital, recovering from a nasty 
motorcycle spill. But Chrysalis Records says plans to release the rock singer's 
new album, "Charmed Life," remain on schedule. 
</P>
<P>
Due out April 17, the aptly-titled record features "Cradle of Love" (due out as 
a single), "Prodigal Blues," "Trouble With the Sweet Stuff," "License to 
Thrill" and a remake of the Doors' "L.A. Woman." Idol's "Cradle of Love" will 
also be on the Elektra soundtrack to "Ford Fairlane," the Andrew (Dice) Clay 
film due out this summer. . . . A Truth in Advertising Raspberry to KLOS-FM, 
which had replacement deejays tell listeners that morning hot-shots Mark &amp; 
Brian were off-the-air last week, allegedly because of a dispute over a 
disciplinary memo from management. The clever ratings ploy was in perfect sync 
with the duo's bad-boy image -- and kept listeners tuning in daily to see if 
the jocks had returned. The reality? Mark &amp; Brian were simply on vacation. 
. . . And our Blunder of the Week goes to Hollywood Reporter reviewer Jeffrey 
Jolson-Colburn, who expressed "disappointment" in his Monday review of the 
recent Tears for Fears concert that the group "didn't perform a few of the 
tunes they created with (Liza Minnelli) for her brilliant 'Results' album . . . 
" Only one problem: Liza made "Results" with the Pet Shop Boys, not Tears for 
Fears. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Billy Idol . . . still hospitalized but leading a charmed life? 
</P>
