<HEADLINE>
<P>
NEW TRANSIT CHIEF MIGHT NEED TIME TO GET UNTRACKED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Alan Kiepper wanted to start off his first day as president of the Transit 
Authority on the right foot. Instead, he started it on the wrong train. 
</P>
<P>
The new subway chief got lost on the F line and ended up in Queens last week 
instead of the TA's headquarters in Brooklyn. 
</P>
<P>
But Kiepper, 10 minutes late for a staff meeting, showed his managerial sense 
of direction by launching a review of train- and station-cleaning standards and 
asking his staff to brainstorm on how to speed up a station-restoration 
program. 
</P>
<P>
Still, Subway Map Reading 101 might be useful. 
</P>
<P>
Before boarding the wrong train in Manhattan, Kiepper took time to stop and 
give directions to a man looking for the No. 6 train. 
</P>
<P>
"I found out later I gave him the wrong directions," Kiepper said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
