<HEADLINE>
<P>
POINT DEDUCTION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Regarding deduction of the cost of points on the refinance of a home residence 
on your income tax, both Robert Bruss, and now Benny L. Kass are giving out 
incorrect information. 
</P>
<P>
While it is true that points are not usually deductible in one year on a 
refinance, but must be amortized over the life of the loan, there are 
exceptions. 
</P>
<P>
Before our refinance this year, I carefully investigated with the IRS, and 
found out that if the points are paid out of separate funds rather than the 
funds advanced by lender through the refinancing, and if a portion of the 
refinance money is used to improve your home, the points may be deducted in 
full in the same year. 
</P>
<P>
With the cost of home remodeling, it is certainly possible to deduct the full 
cost of points on a refinance in the year the loan is obtained, as we are 
doing. You are doing a disservice to your readers not to get this information 
out to them before they refinance, so that they may pay the points out of 
separate funds and thus qualify. 
</P>
<P>
DOROTHY E. FIERING 
</P>
<P>
Thousand Oaks 
</P>
</TEXT>
