<HEADLINE>
<P>
HIS GOAL IS TO SCORE THEM IN WORLD CUP; 
</P>
<P>
SOCCER: WYNALDA MOVES UP FROM DEVELOPMENTAL SQUAD TO STRIKE A BLOW FOR U.S. 
NATIONAL TEAM. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEFF MEYERS, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
His first appearance in a screaming headline occurred 12 years ago when a 
Thousand Oaks newspaper stretched this banner across the top of the sports 
page: "Eric Wynalda -- Soccer Figure at 8." 
</P>
<P>
At the time, Eric's father, David, was surprised by the headline and felt Eric 
really didn't deserve being singled out. Sure, Eric scored 56 goals in leading 
his youth soccer team to a state championship season, "but we thought he was 
just having fun out there. We didn't see him as special," David says. 
</P>
<P>
However, the reporter who wrote the story accompanying the headline was an 
Irish-born soccer expert, David says, "who recognized the things in Eric that 
we couldn't see." 
</P>
<P>
Today, it no longer takes a trained eye to determine that Eric is special. 
Always a prodigious scorer -- 88 goals in three varsity seasons at Westlake 
High and Southern Section 4-A Division offensive player of the year -- Wynalda 
is a strong candidate for the U.S. national team that will compete in the World 
Cup starting June 10 in Italy. 
</P>
<P>
"Eric is a gifted athlete," U.S. Coach Bob Gansler says. 
</P>
<P>
Currently considered the team's No. 1 striker, Wynalda started at forward in 
the last four exhibitions, including a 3-1 loss to the Soviet Union before an 
estimated crowd of 61,000 in Palo Alto last week, and just signed a contract 
with the U.S. Soccer Federation. His presence in the lineup, Gansler says, 
"adds some attacking flair to our team." 
</P>
<P>
But despite Wynalda's scoring skills, his status is surprising -- he wasn't on 
the national team until January. While strikers such as Peter Vermes and Brent 
Goulet were helping the United States to its stunning performance in World Cup 
qualifying last year, Wynalda was playing for the national developmental 
B-team. It took six months before Wynalda was able to move up to the big team. 
</P>
<P>
"Eric caught our attention when he was working with the B-team," Gansler says. 
"We knew he was a talent." 
</P>
<P>
Gansler wanted Wynalda to join the national team for a game against the Soviets 
in Philadelphia last August, but he came down with mononucleosis. The disease 
laid him up for two months and prevented his starting the collegiate season on 
time at San Diego State. In late December, Gansler called Eric at his parents' 
Westlake Village home and asked him to attend a two-week training camp in La 
Jolla. 
</P>
<P>
Wynalda, 6-1, 170, with long sandy-colored hair, was one of 28 players Gansler 
brought to camp. Most of the country's top strikers -- including some who play 
professionally abroad -- were there, but Wynalda stood out "and started to 
shine," Gansler says. By the end of camp, Gansler said Wynalda was his top 
striker but needed international experience. 
</P>
<P>
Wynalda went to Miami with the national team for the Marlboro Cup matches in 
January. But Gansler started a midfielder, Hugo Perez, ahead of Wynalda in the 
opening game against Costa Rica, and Perez played the first 45 minutes in a 2-0 
loss. Wynalda played the last 15 minutes, "made an impact," he says, and 
Gansler told him he had earned a chance to start against Colombia. 
</P>
<P>
Four minutes into the Colombia game, Wynalda, at 20 the youngest starter in the 
lineup, took a pass and went in alone on the Colombian goalkeeper, beating him 
with a quick shot for the only U.S. goal in a 1-1 tie. 
</P>
<P>
But Wynalda doesn't have a lock on a starting job or even a guaranteed backup 
role on the World Cup team. Gansler isn't going to name the final 22-man roster 
until May, after several more international exhibitions. And, according to 
Gansler, Wynalda still needs to improve. 
</P>
<P>
"At times he looks very, very good, and at times he gets caught with his 
concentration waning," Gansler says. "Technically he's fine, but he has to get 
better on the tactical end of things." Then Gansler adds, "I'm betting that 
he's going to get it done." 
</P>
<P>
Wynalda's next test will be March 10 against Finland in Tampa, Fla. "Coach 
Gansler always tells us, 'You're only as good as your last performance,' " 
Wynalda says. "That saying always goes off in my mind. I know if I have a bad 
game he'll give someone else a look." 
</P>
<P>
Most experts say that the problem with American soccer is the lack of skillful 
finishers, players who can score goals. Wynalda is a rare exception, says Chuck 
Clegg, soccer coach at San Diego State. 
</P>
<P>
"Eric's ability to take on a player one-on-one is the best I've ever seen in an 
American," Clegg says. "And to have developed this skill with a purely American 
experience is very unusual." 
</P>
<P>
Wynalda learned to play in the American Youth Soccer Organization. When he was 
5 and his brother Brandt was 7, they joined an AYSO team coached by their 
father. The team's assistant coach was Italian-born Tino Forino, who spoke 
little English but knew how to play the European way. 
</P>
<P>
"Eric was inspired by Tino," says David, who owns a soccer specialty shop in 
Westlake Village. "The kids didn't understand much of what he was saying, but 
he still taught them the basics." 
</P>
<P>
In his junior year at Westlake High, Wynalda was coached by another European, a 
former player from Austria named Rudi Fedimeyer, who was studying American 
soccer for his doctorate degree. Fedimeyer helped refine Wynalda's techniques, 
and by the time Eric enrolled at San Diego State, he was "one of the most 
skillful players we've ever had," Clegg says. 
</P>
<P>
Wynalda stayed at San Diego only three seasons. In his freshman year, he scored 
the winning goal against UCLA in the NCAA Division I tournament quarterfinal 
and led the Aztecs into the final, where they lost to Clemson, 1-0. But last 
December, after the season, Wynalda decided to drop out of school and forgo his 
senior year of soccer. 
</P>
<P>
Only a handful of Americans currently play first division soccer elsewhere in 
the world, but Wynalda made strong connections when he and Aztec teammate 
Marcello Balboa played in a farewell game for Brazilian soccer star Zico last 
December in Brazil. Wynalda says he has offers to play first-division soccer in 
Spain and Holland. 
</P>
<P>
His priority, however, is making the U.S. World Cup team. "I'm very confident 
that I can do some very good things for the team," he says. "I think I bring an 
element of unpredictability to the attack." 
</P>
<P>
A major underdog in the 24-nation tournament, the United States is grouped with 
Czechoslovakia, Austria and host Italy in the opening round. But Wynalda says 
the United States is no longer a pushover. He points out that the national team 
was 8-18-9 in international games in 1988 and 18-6-3 last year. 
</P>
<P>
"That has a lot to do with the confidence we have in ourselves as a soccer 
nation," he says. "We don't go on the field any more trying just to hold our 
own. We expect to win and we don't feel overwhelmed. We don't say, 'Oh, we're 
playing Brazil,' and panic. 
</P>
<P>
"In the qualifying rounds we proved we could play defense. Now we have to 
generate a consistent attack." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Profile 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
WYNALDA, ERIC; SOCCER PLAYERS; WORLD CUP SOCCER; UNITED STATES ATHLETIC TEAMS 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA030490-0220 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 184791 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
March 4, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
